<TEXT>
solidarity and government negotiators said 
tuesday that talks on political and economic reform were threatened 
by the failure of the official trade union alliance to agree on a 
plan to index wages to prices to protect workers incomes 
but both sides expressed hope that agreement still could be 
reached the representatives made their comments in separate 
statements carried by the staterun news agency pap early tuesday 
solidarity leader lech walesa and other top solidarity leaders 
and advisers appeared exhausted after they returned to the roman 
catholic episcopate after 10 hours of talks with interior minister 
gen czeslaw kiszczak and other top government and officials from 
opzz the official trade union alliance 
the situation is relatively dramatic the talks are not 
finished we will continue them today of course there are still 
chances even big ones walesa told reporters waiting outside the 
episcopate 
pap also said the talks would continue tuesday 
it was the second time in less than a week that top 
representatives of both sides met at a government residence in 
magdalenka south of warsaw to discuss issues blocking progress at 
the talks which began feb 6 
the key outstanding issue appears to be a solidarity proposal to 
index wages to prices to protect workers incomes against inflation 
the executive committee of the opzz on monday opposed the 
solidarity plan and called for a lump sum indexation of wages 
the executive committee does not accept the method of 
indexation of wages compensating for only 80 percent of price 
increases particularly as this has been conditioned on the wage 
capacities of work places an opzz statement said 
the opzz warned against the social consequences which the 
introduction of indexation mechanisms agreed by solidarity and 
the authorities could have it does not contribute to a cooling 
down of unrest but can even lead to its aggravation 
solidarity charged that the opzz position presented the state 
of negotiations and the stand of solidarity in a lying and 
irresponsible way 
the solidarity statement also accused the opzz of trying to 
break down the round table and destroying an apparent chance to 
save the country they opzz are playing with poland 
the banned union called on the government to stop raising prices 
until indexation is introduced and called for the legalization of 
solidarity as soon as possible 
however the statement ended on an optimistic note 
solidarity states it is possible to lead the round table to 
the end it lies in polands interests solution of the present 
situation depends on the consequences and imagination of polish 
political authorities 
the government side also expressed its concern over the stance 
of the opzz saying in a statement that solutions proposed in the 
opzz resolution threaten the economy create a danger of social 
conflicts and seriously hinder the process of the round table 
the group that accompanied walesa included journalist tadeusz 
mazowiecki and historian bronislaw geremek union leaders zbigniew 
bujak and wladyslaw frasyniuk political theorists adam michnik and 
jacek kuron as well as gdansk bishop tadeusz goclowski and rev 
alojzy orszulik 
wednesday is the tentative date set for the final agreement on 
legalizing solidarity and introducing a package of political and 
economic reforms according to a communique issued after a meeting 
between the sides march 29 
but solidarity spokesmen have expressed doubt that the target 
can be met 
three groups on economic political and trade union reforms are 
scheduled to meet tuesday mazowiecki said the further top level 
meeting could be held after the conclusion of those discussions 
the broad outline of an agreement was reached some time ago 
in exchange for legalization of solidarity and other independent 
groups that were banned after the december 1981 martial law 
crackdown the opposition would agree to participate in june 
parliament elections that would guarantee the communist party and 
its allies 65 percent of the 460 seats 
a presidency and a senate of about 100 members would be created 
the opposition would be expected to win the senate which would be 
picked in an open democratic vote 
the president would likely be a member of the communist party 
and would be elected jointly by parliament and the senate given the 
strength of the communist party and its allies in the larger 
parliament 
the opposition also would have access to mass media including a 
daily newspaper and two weeklies and at least one program a week on 
national tv and radio 
the opposition wants the authorities to agree to a formula of 
indexing workers wages to compensate for polands unabating 
inflation which topped 60 percent last year 
authorities proposed talks last august during the years second 
nationwide wave of crippling industrial strikes 
they hope agreement will provide poland with political and labor 
stability so economic reforms designed to combat polands 39 
billion foreign debt they also hope agreement will persuade the 
west to invest in poland 
</TEXT>
