<TEXT>
the dollar finished lower against the japanese yen 
today following intervention by the bank of japan while share 
prices hit a new record high on the tokyo stock exchange 
the 225issue nikkei stock average which gained a marginal 
1255 points friday surpassed the 33000point mark for the first 
time and added another 20339 points or 062 percent to finish at 
3304207 
todays index marked the fifth consecutive gain in six days 
dealers said the beginning of japans new business year was 
sparking strong buying interest especially among individual 
investors for most japanese companies the new fiscal year starts 
april 1 
a wellbalanced mixture of supply and demand in the stock 
market as well as stabilized oil prices also encouraged buying 
said a dealer with a securities firm in tokyo speaking on 
condition of anonymity 
trading was active with first section volume estimated at 14 
billion shares among the winners were automobiles chemicals and 
papers 
in currency dealings the dollar closed at 13226 yen down 029 
yen from fridays 13255 yen opening higher at 13318 yen the 
currency plunged while moving in a range of 1322013333 yen 
the bank of japans dollarselling yensupporting intervention 
during early morning trading helped push the dollar down said yuko 
kawai with chemical bank in tokyo 
she said the tokyo market opened with an upward trend following 
dollarbuying in the sydney market which had opened earlier but 
japanese investors sold off their us currency after the japanese 
banks intervention 
the bank of japan sold dollars for yen in tokyo early today for 
the first time since the plaza currency agreement in late 1985 
traders said in the plaza accord monetary authorities for major 
currency nations agreed to bring down the value of the dollar 
which then was trading at about 242 yen 
traders estimated the central bank sold about 10 million the 
bank of japan does not comment officially on its market 
interventions 
finance officials from the socalled group of seven leading 
currency nations met sunday near washington and issued a communique 
saying they had reiterated their commitment to cooperate closely 
on the exchange markets 
the release of the g7 communique today also helped weaken the 
dollar but it did not boost yenbuying incentives in tokyo either 
ms kawai said 
bank of japan governor satoshi sumita was reported today as 
saying the g7 was more concerned about an excessive rise of the 
dollar than an excessive fall 
sumita said the g7 had reaffirmed to the markets its 
determination to keep foreign exchange markets steady 
