<TEXT>
the supreme court today agreed to decide 
whether a maryland mother may be jailed for refusing to reveal the 
whereabouts of her son who authorities fear may be dead 
the justices said they will hear arguments by prosecutors who 
say the need to protect abused children in such cases outweighs a 
parents constitutional right against selfincrimination 
the court also granted an appeal filed in behalf of the womans 
son 
the case dates back to jan 23 1987 when jacqueline 
bouknights threemonthold son maurice was admitted to a baltimore 
hospital with a broken leg and other partially healed fractures 
suspecting the infant had been abused baltimore social workers 
put maurice in foster care and later obtained a court order giving 
the city protective custody of him 
city officials also said ms bouknight suffered from emotional 
problems and had been observed throwing maurice into his crib 
during the infants hospitalization ms bouknight did not dispute 
the citys assertions 
maurice was returned to ms bouknights custody on july 17 
1987 after she agreed not to punish him physically and to undergo 
training in acquiring parenting skills 
but nine months later the social workers said ms bouknight no 
longer was cooperating with them they said maurices father 
recently had been shot to death and that ms bouknight was using 
drugs 
they also said they feared maurice might be dead 
ms bouknight was held in contempt by a judge on april 28 1988 
after she refused to disclose maurices whereabouts the day before 
she told the judge the boy was with her sister in texas but the 
sister said she had not seen maurice 
the judge ordered ms bouknight jailed until she revealed where 
her son is 
the maryland court of appeals by a 52 vote last dec 19 ruled 
that jailing ms bouknight for refusing to disclose information 
about her sons whereabouts violated her constitutional protection 
against selfincrimination 
the state court said in these circumstances if the 
information discloses that maurice is now dead or has been subject 
to criminal abuse as the prosecution candidly fears suspicion 
concededly would focus on bouknight as the criminal agent 
by disclosing the demanded information therefore bouknight 
would in the event a crime had been committed upon maurices 
person be incriminating herself 
chief justice william h rehnquist set aside the state court 
decision pending further review of the case by the full supreme 
court he thus reinstated the contempt citation and the indefinite 
jailing of ms bouknight 
in any event prosecutors said she was behind bars on 
independent grounds a theft conviction that resulted in an 
18month jail sentence 
advocates for children and youth in baltimore joined maryland 
officials in urging the justices to reverse the state courts 
ruling that ms bouknights constitutional rights were violated 
the childrens rights organization said the state court ruling 
could tie the hands of juvenile courts in protecting neglected and 
abused children 
the cases are baltimore department of social services vs 
bouknight 881182 and maurice m vs bouknight 886651 
