<TEXT>
the supreme court today agreed to decide 
whether defense contractors violate a federal conflictofinterest 
law when paying severance to employees who quit to take important 
government jobs 
the court said it will hear appeals by the boeing co and five 
former employees who received 485000 in severance when they left 
to take jobs in the reagan administration 
the 4th us circuit court of appeals last may ordered either 
boeing or the former employees to turn the severance payments over 
to the government 
the appeals court said boeing paid the money to the employees to 
compensate them for taking lowerpaying government jobs 
such payments create at least the appearance of a conflict of 
interest the appeals court said 
we hold that payments made to future federal employees before 
they begin government service can violate federal 
conflictofinterest law if they are made with compensatory 
intent the appeals court said 
government lawyers urged the supreme court to reject the appeals 
by boeing and the five former employees 
the government said the severance payments were classic 
violations of federal law because they were intended to 
encourage the recipients to accept the government positions and 
they were calculated to supplement the recipients federal salaries 
by making up the difference between their government pay and their 
higher pay with boeing 
the five are thomas k jones who received 132000 from boeing 
before he became deputy undersecretary of defense for strategic 
