<TEXT>
the supreme court today let stand a ruling 
that city police officers may be required to undergo random drug 
tests and tests that are part of annual physical examinations 
the justices without comment turned away arguments in behalf 
of washington township nj police officers 
the high court last month handed down its first drugtesting 
decisions upholding drug and alcohol tests for railway workers 
involved in accidents and us customs service employees applying 
for drug enforcement jobs or those jobs that require carrying a 
firearm 
the 3rd us circuit court of appeals dismissing claims the 
washington township tests violate privacy rights ruled last june 
that police officers are part of a highly regulated industry 
subject to such searches even if drug abuse is not suspected 
the appeals court noted that rules specify what police may wear 
how they may cut their hair and when they may smoke 
the 3rd circuit court previously approved random drug tests for 
jockeys because they are part of a highly regulated industry 
the police industry is probably the most highly regulated 
with respect to performance of its employees of any industry in 
new jersey the appeals court said 
it added that police officers exercise the most awesome and 
dangerous power that a democratic state possesses with respect to 
its residents the power to use lawful force to arrest and detain 
them 
in their decisions last week the justices did not decide the 
constitutionality of random drug tests for public employees 
washington township a small suburb of philadelphia adopted 
drug testing for municipal workers in november 1986 in response to 
a call from president reagan for a campaign to assure drugfree 
workplaces 
mayor john robertson said i firmly believe that as employees 
of the taxpayers we have an obligation to show the way toward 
achieving a drugfree workplace 
the policemens benevolent association with support from the 
american civil liberties union said the tests infringe on 
constitutional protections against unlawful searches and seizures 
a federal judge agreed ruling that tests are permissible only 
when there is an individualized reasonable suspicion an 
officer is using drugs 
but the 3rd circuit court reversed that ruling 
in appealing to the supreme court the police union said there 
have been no problems with drugs among municipal employees the 
tests are an improper response to public concern the union said 
heightened public attention to the law enforcement problems 
created by illegal drug trafficking has engendered powerful 
pressures to weaken the constitutional protections long afforded to 
all citizens the union said 
in another case the court without comment let stand the 
firing of james b copeland as a philadelphia police officer 
copeland tested positive for mariujuana or hashish after his 
former girlfriend also a police officer told his superiors he 
used drugs 
the cases are policemens benevolent association vs washington 
township 88706 and copeland vs philadelphia police department 
8866 
