<TEXT>
the supreme court today ruled that a texas 
school boards policy does not violate the voting rights of 
hispanics 
the court by a 72 vote upheld a policy limiting the power of 
a single board member to place an item on the agenda for board 
meetings 
justices byron r white and antonin scalia dissented saying the 
court should hear oral arguments in the case before deciding it 
the school board in victoria texas has seven members since 
1984 five board members have been elected from singlemember 
districts and two in atlarge voting 
theresa gutierrez became the first and only mexicanamerican 
elected to the school board in 1985 she represents a district with 
a 514 percent hispanic population and a 14 percent black 
population 
the school board in 1987 changed its policy for placing items on 
meeting agendas the new policy says the school board president may 
require the approval of two board members also called trustees 
before an item can be added to the agenda for an upcoming meeting 
mrs gutierrez and others in her district said the new policy 
affects the rights of voters she represents by reducing her power 
to recommend agenda items 
she said the federal voting rights act requires that the us 
attorney general approve the policy before it can be implemented 
but a threejudge federal court last year ruled against ms 
gutierrez and her constitutents 
the federal court said the new policys effect on the powers 
of the elected trustees was at most minuscule 
the threejudge court compared the policy to the standard 
parliamentary procedure that requires someone to second any motion 
or resolution before it can be submitted to a vote 
it seems plain to us that if mrs gutierrez is unable to 
persuade even one other trustee to join her in placing a matter on 
the boards agenda she would have no better succeess in procuring 
a second should she have moved it at a meeting the federal court 
said 
also the federal court said the policy in no way singles her 
out for unfavorable procedural treatment 
the case is rojas vs victoria independent school district 
872118 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

