american family to buy a home made its sharpest drop in 15 years 
last month as rising mortgage rates and home prices resulted in a 
loss of purchasing power a real estate trade group said monday 
the national association of realtors said its affordability 
index was at 105 in february down 51 index points from a revised 
1101 in january it was the biggest monthtomonth decline since 
the measure dropped 52 index points from 137 to 1318 in january 
1974 
februarys index level meant that a family earning the median 
income of 32314 annually had 5 percent more income than needed to 
qualify for a mortgage covering 80 percent of the purchase price of 
a medianpriced home 
the median price for an existing home in february was 93100 
meaning half the homes sold for more and half for less februarys 
median price was up 3400 from january 
the mortgage rate used to calculate the index rose to 977 
percent in february from 961 percent representing a composite of 
fixed and adjustable rates 
john a tuccillo chief economist for the realtors said the 
index was likely to decline again in march since mortgage rates 
continued to increase although prices and rates should level off 
later this spring 
the affordability index has been above 100 since it hit 998 in 
may 1986 
for nearly three years housing affordability for the typical 
buyer has been well above the breakeven point said ira gribin 
president of the realtors group but hikes in mortgage rates and 
prices have made buying more difficult 
</TEXT>
