<TEXT>
energy secretary james d watkins on monday 
told congress he expects to give final approval by august to a plan 
for restarting an idled nuclear reactor in south carolina that 
makes materials for atomic weapons 
watkins told a special panel of the house armed service 
committee he had begun reviewing restart recommendations from 
westinghouse electric corp which operates the savannah river site 
reactors under an energy department contract 
he indicated that while he was pleased with westinghouses 
approach to attempting to resolve the safety and managerial 
problems at the site near aiken sc its recommendations fell 
short of what is needed to get the plant back in operation 
we have im afraid a lot more work to do than i see even in 
that plan at this point watkins said 
he said a series of reviews by energy department officials and 
outside experts will be undertaken to ensure a safe resumption of 
tritium production at savannah river tritium is a radioactive gas 
needed in the production of nuclear warheads 
the three active reactors at savannah river have been shut down 
for nearly a year because of safety structural and managerial 
problems a massive campaign has been underway in recent months to 
retrain reactor operators upgrade some plant equipment and 
establish more energy department control of operations there 
earlier this year the energy department had said it was aiming 
to restart the k reactor at savannah river by the end of the year 
it said a further delay would put a serious pinch on supplies of 
tritium thus undermining national security 
watkins appeared to suggest that a restart was not likely until 
1990 although he said it is too early to say for certain when a 
safe restart can be accomplished 
he said he had detected some significant voids in restart 
preparations shortly after he was nominated for the energy job in 
january that we were not addressing in my opinion sufficiently 
and could well have delayed unnecessarily the reactor startup next 
year 
watkins stressed several times during his testimony that much 
work remains to be done before he will be ready to authorize a 
resumption of reactor operations 
the steps we have to take for a safe starting will be totally 
different than anything we have done in the past he said 
watkins also reaffirmed the bush administrations committment to 
winning congressional approval for a 68 billion project to build 
a new generation of tritiumproducing reactors one at savannah 
river and another in idaho to replace the current savannah river 
complex which was built in the early 1950s 
the department has encountered opposition to the plan by some 
legislators and environmental groups critics say no more than one 
new reactor is necessary but watkins said he wants extra 
production capacity in case of emergencies 
this duality makes strategic sense he said since it would 
mean no loss of nuclear capability in the event an earthquake or 
other natural disaster disabled one reactor 
