<TEXT>
the prosecution and defense agreed monday 
that a man who killed six people in a shopping center rampage was 
mentally ill but the prosecutor said it was no excuse 
prosecutor larry holmes told jurors the evidence was so 
overwhelming that william cruse killed with premediation that cruse 
had no other choice but to plead innocent by reason of insanity 
mental illness was the motivator for the crime not its 
justification said holmes arguing that mental illness is not 
enough for acquittal under florida law 
holmess cocounsel assistant state attorney chris white 
argued that cruse had acted out of anger not illness 
hoisting the ruger 223caliber semiautomatic assault rifle used 
in the rampage the prosecutor added that cruse had purchased the 
perfect weapon for mass murder 
the defense contended that cruse 61 was driven by delusions 
about homosexuality and was unable to control his actions when he 
began shooting people at two shopping centers 
public defender marlene alva said cruse was temporarily insane 
and therefore couldnt be convicted of premeditated firstdegree 
murder 
you have here before you a madman a crazy person someone who 
went berserk on april 23 1987 she said 
six people including two policemen were killed and 10 were 
wounded in the bloody rampage in palm bay on floridas east coast 
the state is seeking the death penalty on six counts of murder 24 
counts of attempted murder and two counts of kidnapping 
after arguments by attorneys the jury was to return tuesday 
morning for instructions by the judge before deliberating cruses 
fate 
much of the morning monday was spent in argument over whether to 
admit testimony by tampa forensic psychiatrist robert berland 
berland told the court out of the presence of the jury that 
cruse was so psychotically fearful of attack that he always 
carried a gun always slept with a gun always kept a knife 
ready for a quick draw 
white objected to the introduction of the testimony at this 
point in the 4weekold trial saying much of the information had 
been obtained by berland in midmarch after the trial started and 
from cruse himself 
circuit judge john antoon overruled the objection on hearsay but 
agreed the defense could have presented such findings earlier 
to do so now antoon said would give the defendant an unfair 
advantage or would force the state to bring in other testimony 
and allow the war of experts to go on and on 
four other psychiatrists and a psychologist testified 
disagreeing sharply on whether cruse legally was temporarily insane 
when he systematically picked off victim after victim at two 
shopping centers 
under floridas definition of temporary insanity the defense 
must show that cruse not only was mentally ill but did not know 
the consequences of his actions or that they were wrong 
