editors note socrates today might have his own parking space 
and his name on an office door as a professional ethicist instead 
of walking barefoot in the streets of athens to proclaim his 
message of know thyself from wall street to washington 
classrooms to newsrooms the emphasis is on ethics these days as 
one consultant put it ethics is redhot right now 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
a lear jet whines into the south bend ind airport to pluck a 
theologian from the notre dame campus for consultation with senior 
management of a west coast timber giant on environmental ethics 
in fort lauderdale fla a stretch limo with a bar and tv set 
whisks maryknoll priest ed wroblewski who has spent much of his 
life in the african mission fields off to join corporate 
executives at a weeklong seminar on values and ethics 
as dawn breaks over capitol hill more than a dozen congressmen 
sit down at a prayer breakfast to meditate on government service 
which president bush in his first week in office declared to be 
noble calling a public trust and appointed an eightmember 
commission to frame a new code of ethics for enlightened official 
behavior 
on the other side of the potomac beefy backs and burly linemen 
with the washington redskins gather in cornerback darrell greens 
living room to pray for fellow athletes fighting a drug habit 
manhattans trinity church from its vantage point at the head 
of wall street now runs an outreach center headed by dr david 
schmidt an ethicist to help firms like standard oil and champion 
international develop programs for responsible corporate behavior 
the american medical association reports that 90 percent of the 
countrys major hospitals now have a staff ethics consultant or 
regularly meeting ethics committee 
ethics is redhot right now says the rev james joyce at 
the jesuit office around the corner from the new york stock 
exchange where at noon on tuesdays investment bankers market 
analysts and various management types bring a brownbag lunch to 
chew over the moral implications of tender offers forced 
acquisitions plant closings and insider trading 
ethics is certainly enjoying a huge comeback says 
philosopher lisa newton of connecticuts fairfield university 
its almost a fad says schmidt 
beginning this school year harvard business school now requires 
all firstyear mba candidates to take a decision making and 
ethical values course taught by nine senior faculty members 
former securities and exchange commission chairman john shad gave 
harvard a 20 million endowment to teach future traders and money 
managers the difference between right and wrong 
barry bingham jr former editor and publisher of the 
courierjournal in louisville ky has launched fineline a 
newsletter for professionals in print and broadcast news dealing in 
actual case histories of ethical problems confronting the media 
deni elliott director of dartmouths institute of ethics has 
spent months in the newsrooms of the philadelphia inquirer the 
courierjournal wchstv in portland maine and similar clients 
coaching journalists on how to think morally when the tough 
calls come in near deadline should we reveal the name of a rape 
victim go with the gory pictures of a fatal accident on the 
interstate protect the source blowing the whistle on city contract 
scandals 
lisa newton of fairfield university wrote the study guide for 
public broadcastings critically acclaimed 10part series on ethics 
in america that featured such diverse panelists as former us 
attorney rudolph giuliani supreme court justice antonin scalia 
takeover specialist t boone pickens former un delegate jeane 
kirkpatrick gen william westmoreland surgeon general c everett 
koop civil rights activist c vernon mason and katharine graham of 
the washington post 
schmidt of the trinity center spent several months going through 
the inhouse training program of a leading wall street investment 
firm to be able to talk their language and serve as midwife 
at the birth of a values program 
there are companies now that have positions of high corporate 
responsibility staffed by theologians and philosophers he says 
socrates today might have his own parking space and his name on 
an office door as an ethicist instead of walking barefoot in the 
streets of athens to proclaim his message of know thyself 
like jesuit john langan at georgetowns kennedy institute of 
ethics he might be a values consultant to chemical bank the 
nations fourthlargest 
or like chuck powers he might have his own consulting firm 
resources for responsible management to provide handson 
training for business managers and policy makers concerned about 
whether the golden rule is obsolete in drawing the bottom line 
powers epitomizes the pilgrims progress of the modern ethician 
or ethicist as they are now interchangeably called in personnel 
job descriptions he went from the faculty of the yale divinity 
school to vice president for public policy at cummins engine the 
indiana diesel manufacturer that was the first to introduce a 
companywide ethics training program 
powers next was recruited by industry and government to found 
the health effects institute and clean sites innovative 
nonprofit organizations looking into problems of motor vehicle 
exhausts and cleaning up toxic waste dumps 
his wife barbara ley toffler a psychologist in organizational 
behavior with clients such as american can gte aetna and even the 
internal revenue service is his partner in the consulting firm 
which does not advertise but depends on client referrals 
is there a livelihood in ministering to the troubled soul of 
industry 
the bottom line is that we made money last year says 
barbara toffler 
webster defines ethics as the philosophy of human conduct with 
emphasis on the determination of right from wrong ethics pitches 
its tent on the high ground beyond and sometimes contrary to what 
the law allows 
fred friendly the former cbs news boss who hosted the pbs 
ethics series remembers well a gentle scolding by supreme court 
justice potter stewart the trouble with your profession 
journalism is that you are all confused about what you have a 
right to do under the constitution and the right thing to do 
