william sloane coffin who recommended that students burn their 
draft cards shut down the city of washington 
on house calls to industry ethicist newton shies from the 
designation philosopher thats someone who stands around the 
water cooler all day she says a cartoon on her office door 
comes closer to describing the role of the ethicist in industry a 
harried executive is pushing a button on the intercom and intoning 
miss wattles will you send someone in who knows right from 
wrong 
lately leaders in the fields of government medicine law 
engineering computers journalism have been pushing the button for 
an expert consultant to help write some ethical guidelines or deal 
with cases of misconduct 
a recent example of job opportunities for a latterday socrates 
is the nationwide search conducted by floridas poynter institute 
for a theologian or philosopher to head up its ethics center three 
other branches of this highly respected institute concentrate on 
improving skills and standards of working journalists in writing 
graphics and management 
we believe people at every level can be trained to think about 
ethical dilemmas says institute president robert haiman so 
when that big call comes up at 1040 and youre going to press at 
11 you have a more orderly way to approach it 
a lot of these ethical calls have to be made by street 
reporters were talking about reportorial behavior is it ok to 
read upside down on somebodys desk is it ok to open a guys file 
cabinet while hes out of the office is it ok to lie about who you 
are to pretend youre an ambulance attendant or whatever 
some at the top of the executive ladder argue that ethics 
training should begin at the very bottom long before college or 
professional school 
if an mba candidate doesnt know the difference between 
honesty and crime between lying and telling the truth wrote ibm 
chairman john akers in a recent issue of the sloane management 
review then business school in all probability will not 
produce a convert 
akers finds it ludicrous that even divinity schools and law 
