<TEXT>
earth berms on either side of a 
highway cut noise levels in nearby neighborhoods better than 
barrier walls a researcher says 
these are even more effective if they are covered with grass 
or other vegetation because the carpet of plants absorbs the 
sound said sabih hayek a professor of engineering science and 
mechanics without vegetation the berms simply reflect most of the 
sound back onto the roadway 
most trees increase noise to neighborhoods near busy 
thoroughfares because sound is reflected off leaves he said fir 
trees will work better because their needles do not reflect sound 
in fact they absorb sound 
artificial walls of concrete fiberglass or wood reflect noise 
back onto the roadway or over the barrier said hayek whose 
research was sponsored by the national cooperative highway research 
program of the transportation research board representing 50 state 
highway departments 
it is possible to cut as much noise as you want using noise 
barriers hayek said however costs increase dramatically with 
the increase in desired noise reduction a 15foothigh wall 
costs 200 to 250 a foot to build 
we have tested noise barriers covered with materials that 
absorb sound but the added cost of construction is notical 
compared with the slight increase in noise reduction achieved with 
absorbent barriers he said 
double walls decrease noise levels behind them threefold over a 
single wall and horizontal overhangs on vertical walls also can 
greatly decrease noise levels but are very expensive to buildhe 
said 
