sound after state officials raised concerns spokesman rick meidt 
said 
night traffic was allowed sunday for the first time since the 
exxon valdez disaster but after a monday meeting the coast guard 
decided again to limit traffic until all agencies are satisfied 
that alyeska pipeline service co the operator of the valdez 
terminal has the equipment to handle another spill meidt said 
if something were to happen lets make sure we have enough 
gear there to respond he said 
the coast guard cut traffic in half through prince william sound 
after the valdez ran aground march 24 spilling more than 10 
million gallons of crude oil into the water 
valdez is the only port from which north slope oil is shipped 
the partial closure reduced north slope crude deliveries of 2 
million barrels a day to fewer than 1 million causing west coast 
refinery shortages and higher oil prices 
the coast guard said sunday that restrictions would remain in 
effect until the valdez was emptied of its remaining oil probably 
tuesday but the agency decided later sunday to lift the daylight 
restriction 
other restrictions such as allowing only one tanker at a time 
through the area and requiring an escort of two tug boats remain 
in effect 
meidt said valdez averages three tankers a day and with 
additional tug boats were not too far away from that 
</TEXT>
