<TEXT>
the citizens and southern corp parent 
corporation of georgias camps bank announced monday that its board 
has decided to fight an uninvited takeover attempt by the giant 
ncnb corp which would create the nations sixthlargest banking 
concern 
the atlantabased bank holding company in a statement termed 
the ncnb stock swap offer inadequate and said camps present 
management is better able to serve the banks customers 
shareholders and communities than ncnb 
we have managed this bank for service growth profitability 
and longterm service to shareholders not for a quick sale camps 
chairman and chief executive officer bennett a brown said the 
board of directors and the management have concluded that this 
offer is clearly inadequate and not in the best interests of camps 
shareholders customers and employees 
ncnb the southeasts largest banking company surprised camps 
late last thursday with a 24 billion stock offer for the 
atlantabased bank camps management was cool to the idea from the 
start 
it was unsolicited said camps chief financial officer james 
d dixon it was uninvited 
in a statement monday night ncnb corp called its offer fair 
and generous and said its legal advisers felt there is no 
regulatory block to such an acquisition 
we are determined to proceed and request the camps board to 
reconsider our offer and promptly authorize negotiations the 
release said 
in its official offer ncnb had told camps it wanted to begin 
active merger discussions within five business days that now 
is unlikely to happen 
camps board in addition to voting unanimously to reject the ncnb 
offer also decided in its meeting monday to adopt a new article in 
the corporations bylaws under georgias business combination act 
preventing any major shareholders from combining with the 
corporation for five years unless certain conditions are met 
the bid for camps followed a highly publicized push by the 
charlotte ncbased ncnb into texas last year buying into the 
republic bank corp of dallas a combined ncnb and camps would create 
a formidable bank with 76 billion in assets ncnb officials 
characterized their buyout offer as a friendly one and vowed to 
leave camps managers and its name in place in georgia 
under ncnbs plan each camps shareholder would bet 1075 shares 
of ncnb common stock for each of their camps shares 
</TEXT>
